## Encoder

```rust
pub struct HdcPass {
    layer: LayerKind,
    codebook: Box<dyn BaseCodebook>,
    cache: Arc<Mutex<HashMap<[u8; 32], [u8; D/8]>>>,
}

impl EnrichmentPass for HdcPass {
    fn name(&self) -> &str { match self.layer { LayerKind::Ast => "hdc_ast", ... } }
    fn depends_on(&self) -> &[&str] { &["tree-sitter"] }
    fn reads(&self) -> &[&str] { &["nodes", "_ast"] }
    fn writes(&self) -> &[&str] { &["_hdc", "_hdc_subtree_cache"] }

    fn run(&self, conn: &Connection, source_dir: &Path, scope: Option<&[String]>) -> Result<EnrichmentStats> {
        // Post-order walk every function-scoped subtree:
        // - for each subtree, compute content_hash
        // - if cache hit → reuse hypervector
        // - else: compute via codebook, cache it
        // - write to _hdc(scope_id, layer_kind=self.layer, hv, basis=parse_version)
        ...
    }
}
```

## Bidi-enabling property

The `_hdc_subtree_cache` is what makes `op_hdc_unbind` (in hdc-5) work. Every subtree at every depth gets its hypervector cached keyed by content-hash. To unbind: query the cache for the role-permuted child slot → cleanup memory finds the codebook entry.

Without this cache, we have forward encoding only — no recovery, no cluster explanation. The math-friend review made this load-bearing.

