File: rs/ll-open/hdc/src/sheaf.rs, function merkle_root, lines 499-508.

The empty-complex sentinel is built as:
  let seed = blake3_seed(&buf);   // blake3_seed returns u64 — only the FIRST 8 bytes of the blake3 hash
  let mut out = [0u8; 32];
  out[..8].copy_from_slice(&seed.to_le_bytes());
  return out;  // bytes [8..32] are ALL ZERO

blake3_seed (util.rs:133-137) truncates the blake3 hash to a u64 by taking the first 8 bytes. The resulting sentinel therefore has only 64 bits of entropy; the upper 24 bytes are structurally zero.

The module docstring calls this a 'domain-tagged empty root' that is 'distinguishable from blake3("") at the type level'. The distinguishability claim is only true to 64-bit security, not 128-bit. Any two distinct domain tags whose blake3 hashes share the same first 8 bytes (a 2^64 collision) would produce the same sentinel — much weaker than the implied full-hash guarantee.

Additionally, any real leaf whose full blake3 hash happened to have 24 trailing zero bytes (probability ~2^-192, negligible) would compare equal to this sentinel, which is a theoretical — not practical — collision.

Fix sketch: replace lines 502-507 with a direct full-hash sentinel:
  let mut buf = b"hdc-sheaf-empty".to_vec(); buf.push(0u8);
  return blake3::hash(&buf).into();
This removes the u64 truncation and gives a genuine 256-bit domain-tagged sentinel. Also update blake3_seed's call sites in util.rs to clarify it is a 64-bit seed, not a full collision-resistant hash, to prevent this pattern from recurring.
